Verify contract per §E.9:
  ✓ Worker vitest covers the two new tools (4 tests each + 4 for the
    jwt helper)
  ✓ API vitest covers draft-from-chat (7 cases: auth, cross-ws, CREATE,
    sessionId-in-inputs, PUT version bump, 409 not_a_draft, 404 unknown)
  ✓ Live e2e: CREATE → dry-run with captured intent → PUT revise →
    activate flips status → cleanup
  ✗ Integration test from a real chat session (LLM driving
    propose_automation → user iteration → activate_automation) —
    deferred to E.10 where the full lifecycle smoke runs in a real
    chat. The worker tools, JWT minting, and api endpoints are
    independently green; the LLM-driven path composes them.

Plumbing notes:
  - Worker JWT minting matches verifyWorkspaceToken's claim shape:
    workspace_id, account_id, plan, seat_status (string ISO), iat, exp.
    Default 5-min TTL; per-call mint is the security model.
  - The draft-from-chat handler defaults missing `triggers` to
    [{type:'manual'}] and `outputs` to [], so the agent can POST a
    minimal `{name, goal}` spec on the first iteration.
  - Conservative approval gate on activate_automation: ALWAYS required
    by default. Operators can short-circuit via the D.9 "YES ALWAYS"
    remember-rule path once they've activated one automation in a
    workspace.

Deferred:
  - E.9 lands the SAME-workspace authoring path. Cross-workspace
    sharing (one workspace publishing a draft another can fork) is
    explicitly §10 non-goal.
  - The worker tool path forwards `sessionId: ctx.runId` to the
    api — the api stores it in inputs._draftFromChatSessionId so
    the preview UI can correlate. A future UI consumer would
    surface that linkage; not built here.
